            <div id="primary-content">
              <a name="198466"></a><h1>Tax Free Childcare</h1>





<h2>Introduction</h2>
<p>Following a review of support for working families, the government has announced that from autumn 2015, the existing childcare voucher scheme (also known as employer supported childcare) will be replaced by a tax-free childcare scheme.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; This scheme will be open to all households in which both parents work but do not receive support through tax credits or Universal Credit.&nbsp; This is subject to both parents meeting a minimum income level (approx. &pound;50 per week on average) but not being an additional rate taxpayer (earning in excess of &pound;150,000 per annum).&nbsp; Households that receive tax credits or Universal Credit can instead get support through those systems.</p>
<p>The existing childcare voucher scheme will be closed to new members from the point at which tax-free childcare is launched.&nbsp;&nbsp; An exact date for the launch of tax-free childcare and therefore the closure of the childcare voucher scheme has yet to be announced by the government.</p>
<p>Parents who already use the childcare voucher scheme will be able to continue to remain in the scheme for as long as their employer agrees to run the scheme.&nbsp; <u>The University of Oxford has agreed that it will continue to run the scheme for the foreseeable future</u>.&nbsp; If, however, you move employers after Tax-Free Childcare is introduced in autumn 2015 you will no longer be entitled to Employer-Supported Childcare.</p>
<p>For a copy of the full government consultation on tax-free childcare see: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/318953/PU1607_Tax_free_Childcare_response.pdf">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/318953/PU1607_Tax_free_Childcare_response.pdf</a></p>
<p>The tax-free childcare implementation team in Whitehall is currently working on a communications campaign to ensure that families can make fully informed choices about their childcare.&nbsp;&nbsp; This website will be updated as Childcare Services receives further information on the scheme.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>
<h2>University of Oxford nursery fees salary sacrifice scheme (Workplace nursery scheme)&nbsp;</h2>
<p>Workplace nurseries are not impacted by this change to tax-free childcare.&nbsp; Families who currently benefit from paying for a University nursery place via salary sacrifice will continue to be able to do so.&nbsp; Eligible new parents offered a University place via Childcare Services will also be able to pay using the workplace nursery salary sacrifice scheme.&nbsp; This will continue to realise considerable tax savings for parents.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <u>Payments for your University nursery provision will continue to be managed via the Childcare Services and your payroll team.<em>&nbsp; </em></u></p>
<p>The University of Oxford&rsquo;s workplace nursery agreement&nbsp; covers all University nurseries (Bradmore Road, Jack Straws Lane , Mansion House and Woodstock Road), as well as the University-owned spaces with Bright Horizons (formerly KidsUnlimited), Oxford Montessori Schools, Co-operative Childcare and Childbase.&nbsp; Under current legislation, the scheme only applies to nurseries where the employer takes part in "financing and managing the provision of the care&rdquo;. Employees using other nurseries are therefore not eligible for the scheme.</p>
<p>The tax savings that parents receive via the workplace nursery scheme (salary sacrifice) will still, in the large majority of cases, result in greater tax savings than that provided by tax-free childcare.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
